How RDG appplies to religion structurally (SID/PED triads)
201.7 – Systems theory, structural analysis of religion
-------------------------------------

This file documents how RDG (Relational Dynamical Geometry)
applies to religion as a structural system using two 
complementary frameworks.

RDG provides a complete relational geometry of belief 
systems by modeling how religious structures evolve, how 
power and authority operate within them, and how doctrinal
systems change under pressure or new evidence.

The framework essentially treats religion as a dynamical 
system with measurable relational properties, allowing for 
formal analysis of religious institutional change and 
belief evolution.

-------------------------------------

RDG is generator-based and closure-first, meaning:

  Belief systems can be treated as closure operators on propositions.
  Belief revision becomes a Q‑moderated dynamic.
  Conflicts between beliefs become interaction geometries.
  Authority becomes a flux engine (MFE-compatible).
  Orthodoxy becomes an evaluation filter.

RDG-SID (Structure–Interaction–Dynamics)

Religion contains:

Structure — doctrines, roles, institutions
Interaction — rituals, obligations, authority relations
Dynamics — conversion, schism, reform, transmission

These map cleanly to SID.

RDG-PED (Power–Evaluation–Dynamics)
Religious systems also contain:

Power(M,F) — authority, hierarchy, charisma
Evaluation(p,P) — moral judgment, purity systems, orthodoxy
Dynamics(Q_slice) — historical evolution, doctrinal drift, ritual stabilization

These map to PED.

Thus RDG can model religion as a relational dynamical system.

How RDG applies: SID/PED mapping
SID (Structure–Interaction–Dynamics)
Structure — core beliefs, axioms, categories
Interaction — how beliefs relate, conflict, reinforce
Dynamics — belief revision, drift, collapse, bifurcation

PED (Power–Evaluation–Dynamics)
Power(M,F) — epistemic authority, prestige, institutional influence
Evaluation(p,P) — filters for valid reasoning, orthodoxy, coherence
Dynamics(Q_slice) — how belief systems evolve under pressure or new evidence

This gives a complete relational geometry of belief systems.
